The paper proposes a protocol for preserving privacy in distributed optimization, which is a topic that falls under the category of machine learning (cs.LG). The privacy aspect of the protocol suggests that it may also belong to the category of cryptography and security (cs.CR). The protocol involves communication between agents, which suggests that it may also belong to the category of distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC). The paper also mentions connectivity of the communication topology, which suggests that it may belong to the category of information theory (cs.IT). Finally, the paper proposes a privacy mechanism that can be combined with any non-private distributed optimization algorithm, which suggests that it may also belong to the category of social and information networks (cs.SI).
